# Security Conventions

## Secrets Management

Secrets are stored in exactly one canonical location per layer:

| Layer | Location | Gitignored? |
|---|---|---|
| Terraform | `terraform/*.tfvars` | ✅ Yes |
| Lambda runtime | AWS Secrets Manager | N/A |
| iOS | `mobile/Arc Agent/Arc Agent/Secrets.swift` | ✅ Yes |
| React dev | `static_site/.env.local` | ✅ Yes |

**Never** hardcode secrets in source files, Terraform resources, or comments.

## API Authentication

Every API Gateway route uses `authorization_type = "CUSTOM"` (custom Lambda authorizer). The authorizer validates `x-api-key` against Secrets Manager. No unauthenticated routes are permitted.

## Log Redaction

The shared `logger` in `@sprint/shared` auto-redacts keys: `githubToken`, `x-api-key`, `authorization`, `password`, `secret`, `token`. Do not log request bodies that may contain these fields directly.

## Error Messages

Use `toPublicError(err)` before returning errors to clients. This prevents stack traces and internal implementation details from leaking.

## CORS

The CORS `allow_origins` is restricted to `https://<env>.<domain>`. Wildcard origins (`*`) are not permitted in production.

## S3

Results bucket: SSE-S3 encryption, versioning enabled, 90-day lifecycle on non-current versions. Public access blocked. CloudFront frontend bucket is served via OAC only — no public bucket policy.
